17
00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:02.000
a major category of immunotherapy resistance.

18
00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:06.340
And that is this notion that, was surprising at first,

19
00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:10.360
these findings were made 15 years ago, that

20
00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:14.400
when we started to study the immunobiology of the tumor microenvironment in real

21
00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:18.160
patient samples, we realized that a major subset of

22
00:01:18.220 --> 00:01:22.170
patients had at baseline this smoldering immune response against their tumor.

23
00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:26.500
And it's important to keep in mind the components of the immune

24
00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:30.500
system that are present in those, what we call T cell inflamed tumors.

25
00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:33.900
It includes CD8 T cells, CD8 positive T cells.

26
00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:36.000
There are other T cells there as well.

27
00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:40.020
It goes beyond alpha beta T cells. There are gamma delta T cells and K

28
00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:40.420
cells.

29
00:01:41.660 --> 00:01:45.640
And some of those CD8 T cells are tumor antigen specific,

30
00:01:46.180 --> 00:01:49.340
not all of them. There are bystander T cells in those tumors as well.

31
00:01:50.380 --> 00:01:54.000
It's not clear functionally if they're contributing anything

32
00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:55.940
positively or negatively.

33
00:01:56.920 --> 00:01:57.260
And

34
00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:02.080
just probing the number of T cells in a tumor is not enough to

35
00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:02.920
understand

36
00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:07.740
the process that's happening. In some tumors, most of the T cells are

37
00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:11.609
irrelevant T cells. There also are chemokines and

38
00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:15.460
cytokines, chemokines that are responsible for recruiting

39
00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:17.470
the CD8 T cells,

40
00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:19.460
and other components.

41
00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:24.920
These T cell inflamed tumors have dendritic cells, and the most important dendritic

42
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.860
cell subset are the BD3 lineage CDC1 cells.

43
00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:33.460
And we've shown recently, and others have as well, that there are clusters of

44
00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:37.370
those CD8 T cells and BD3 dendritic cells in these T cell inflamed

45
00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:41.230
tumors, and that's a predictor of anti-PD-1 efficacy because

46
00:02:41.560 --> 00:02:45.340
it's the dendritic cells that give a positive signal to the T cells once you

47
00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:47.780
block PD-1, and then the T cells expand.

48
00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:50.800
That's the accelerator when you remove your foot off the brake.

49
00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:54.580
And these tumors also have a type I interferon gene signature.

50
00:02:54.940 --> 00:02:58.680
The type I interferons are made by myeloid cells, by dendritic cells.

51
00:02:59.140 --> 00:03:00.660
In mice, it's mostly dendritic cells.

52
00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:03.440
It could be other myeloid cells in these tumors.

53
00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:07.000
And mechanistically, you need the type I interferon signaling

54
00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:10.840
to get the dendritic cells going to cross-present antigen

55
00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:13.180
to the T cells. So these

56
00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:18.120
key elements are in the T cell inflamed tumors and the non-T

57
00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:20.420
cell inflamed tumors lack those elements.

58
00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.420
And so when we think about how to correct

59
00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:28.180
this defect, how do you overcome the

60
00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:31.320
deficiencies in the non-T cell inflamed tumors?

61
00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:35.040
A lot of the work has focused on putting things back.

62
00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:39.260
Can you activate an innate immune pathway, with

63
00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:41.200
TLR agonists, with

64
00:03:42.060 --> 00:03:44.320
STING agonists, as we've done?

65
00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:47.420
It turns out those interventions

66
00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:52.320
have limited efficacy because they're not sufficient to make a

67
00:03:52.360 --> 00:03:56.060
cold tumor hot. I think you need the right cells there as well.

68
00:03:56.500 --> 00:03:58.940
For CpG, you need plasmacytoid dendritic cells.

69
00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:03.040
For a STING agonist, we know you need CDC1 cells in the tumor for a STING

70
00:04:03.080 --> 00:04:04.480
agonist to work pre-clinically.

71
00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:08.620
So, putting things back is still ongoing.

72
00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:12.109
There are more clever ways that are being pursued to get

73
00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:14.609
the good stuff into

74
00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:18.010
the non-T cell inflamed tumors. And then

75
00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:21.780
another consideration is

76
00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:27.300
that our anti-PD-1 responders

77
00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:29.180
fall into the first category, right?

78
00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:33.440
Beginning with reactivation of T cells that are

79
00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:34.860
already in the tumor microenvironment.

80
00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:40.500
Okay, so putting stuff back is ongoing, but that's only half

81
00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:43.980
of the picture. These are just data to

82
00:04:44.020 --> 00:04:45.050
support that

83
00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:49.900
the efficacy of single agent anti-PD-1 is

84
00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:53.420
enriched in patients who have this activated T cell gene signature

85
00:04:54.400 --> 00:04:57.980
characterized by gamma interferon, gamma interferon-induced genes at baseline.

86
00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:01.440
That's true beyond melanoma, where I work, but head and neck cancer,

87
00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:03.430
gastric cancer, and others.

88
00:05:04.240 --> 00:05:07.860
And so it means that the major subset of

89
00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:11.700
tumors that are refractory to anti-PD-1

90
00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:14.440
efficacy have the cold tumor phenotype.

91
00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:18.900
I want to add that we're putting a review paper together about this

92
00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:22.720
now that we're viewing the spontaneous anti-tumor

93
00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:25.030
immunity when you see it like this,

94
00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:30.110
really resembles autoimmunity. And so we're starting to think that

95
00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:31.920
this is the exception, not the rule.

96
00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:36.040
Some patients are more predisposed to make an autoimmune reaction

97
00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:36.620
against their

98
00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:40.969
tumor because of germline genetics, microbiome composition.

99
00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:45.660
And so that viewing spontaneous anti-tumor immunity

100
00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:49.500
through this lens of autoimmunity is useful for the way we're thinking about

101
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:50.480
the problem.

102
00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:54.400
Okay, so those are the introductory comments.

103
00:05:54.500 --> 00:05:57.020
You can reset my clock, although I won't go over.

104
00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:02.056
To now talk aboutAre there bad things

105
00:06:02.096 --> 00:06:03.356
present in the cold tumors?

106
00:06:04.416 --> 00:06:08.316
And so, do we have to give good stuff back

