Thank you so much. It's a fantastic talk.

498
00:29:00.170 --> 00:29:02.630
I personally was looking forward to you singing, but it's okay.

499
00:29:03.690 --> 00:29:04.090
Next year.

500
00:29:04.890 --> 00:29:05.230
ASCO.

501
00:29:05.430 --> 00:29:09.130
Yeah. So my question is along the same lines of

502
00:29:09.150 --> 00:29:11.530
polarization of myeloid populations

503
00:29:12.190 --> 00:29:15.650
in tumor types that are particularly immune

504
00:29:16.090 --> 00:29:16.470
cold.

505
00:29:18.330 --> 00:29:22.280
Immune checkpoint blockade is often combined with chemotherapy, and

506
00:29:22.290 --> 00:29:25.950
part of the rationale there being that chemotherapy can potentiate this

507
00:29:25.960 --> 00:29:28.950
anti-tumoral immune response, turn the tumor more hot,

508
00:29:29.630 --> 00:29:33.110
engage cytosolic DNA release and sensing, so on and so forth,

509
00:29:33.140 --> 00:29:35.770
and part of that is certainly myeloid cell

510
00:29:36.170 --> 00:29:39.590
repolarization. Any thought as

511
00:29:39.610 --> 00:29:43.380
to how that might play a role into some of the results that

512
00:29:43.430 --> 00:29:44.570
you're presenting here?

513
00:29:44.690 --> 00:29:44.740
Yeah.

514
00:29:44.740 --> 00:29:48.450
And could that potentially be, I guess, a wise strategy in this case?

515
00:29:48.510 --> 00:29:52.150
Yeah, I guess I'm more attracted to, let's say,

516
00:29:52.190 --> 00:29:54.630
interventions with greater precision than chemotherapy.

517
00:29:55.210 --> 00:29:55.530
And,

518
00:29:57.050 --> 00:30:00.810
what we're kind of pushing towards is to understand the proportion,

519
00:30:01.070 --> 00:30:04.870
the best we can by these transcriptional profiles, of the tissue-resident

520
00:30:04.890 --> 00:30:08.710
macrophages versus monocyte-derived macrophages in different cancers.

521
00:30:09.230 --> 00:30:12.230
And some of the cancers that I think are really densely resistant

522
00:30:13.150 --> 00:30:16.790
to checkpoint blockade are probably just

523
00:30:16.850 --> 00:30:20.410
loaded with, and sort of protected by, the tissue

524
00:30:20.490 --> 00:30:21.070
repair,

525
00:30:22.230 --> 00:30:25.882
tissue-resident macrophages, which I think are harder-To manipulate, right?

526
00:30:25.962 --> 00:30:28.982
Because they're there to protect the tissue

527
00:30:29.082 --> 00:30:30.242
and

528
00:30:31.102 --> 00:30:34.962
discourage inflammation. So my prediction is that,

529
00:30:36.142 --> 00:30:39.742
let's say standard breast cancer, pancreatic cancer, colon

530
00:30:39.782 --> 00:30:43.302
cancer, maybe prostate cancer. Larry's going to talk about, we'll see what

531
00:30:43.342 --> 00:30:46.842
his extended story is going to be, are going to have more

532
00:30:47.302 --> 00:30:50.602
tissue-resident macrophages that are harder to shift, I think.

533
00:30:50.942 --> 00:30:51.942
But this GPNMB,

534
00:30:53.742 --> 00:30:56.062
accidental discovery could be one way.

535
00:30:56.742 --> 00:31:00.362
And I think we have to stop the questions, unless you have a quick one.

536
00:31:00.962 --> 00:31:03.242
Because I'm chairing too, so I have to regulate myself.

537
00:31:03.422 --> 00:31:03.562
So

538
00:31:04.482 --> 00:31:07.482
GNPB has a functional role, but you think

539
00:31:07.622 --> 00:31:11.402
SPP1, which is on the same macrophages, is more like a

540
00:31:11.462 --> 00:31:13.302
marker and no functional role?

541
00:31:13.542 --> 00:31:16.802
Oh, I don't know. We haven't studied the function of SPP1.

542
00:31:16.942 --> 00:31:20.252
So that was a quick one. All right. So thank you, Dr.

543
00:31:20.442 --> 00:31:21.342
Gajewski, for

544
00:31:22.422 --> 00:31:26.222
an insightful talk. And the second speaker of

545
00:31:26.282 --> 00:31:29.641
the session will be Daniel Pieper from the

546
00:31:29.662 --> 00:31:33.522
Netherlands Cancer Institute, who's going to discuss more of a peripheral

547
00:31:33.642 --> 00:31:37.182
blood-based discovery platform for response versus resistance.

548
00:31:40.262 --> 00:31:40.742
Thank you, Tom.

549
00:31:41.722 --> 00:31:42.162
Good morning.

550
00:31:44.622 --> 00:31:48.502
As we've seen also at this conference, immunotherapy

551
00:31:49.182 --> 00:31:52.042
has really shaped and improved the field.

552
00:31:52.702 --> 00:31:56.462
But in spite of this success, we also see that many patients

553
00:31:56.482 --> 00:31:59.402
still fail to respond durably.

554
00:32:00.422 --> 00:32:00.782
And

555
00:32:02.182 --> 00:32:06.022
that's why the focus of my lab is

556
00:32:06.122 --> 00:32:08.822
on two major goals in cancer immunology.

557
00:32:09.402 --> 00:32:12.722
First is that we want to address the mechanisms that drive

558
00:32:12.762 --> 00:32:16.682
immunotherapy resistance. And secondly, we are interested

559
00:32:16.722 --> 00:32:20.702
to identify and discover new targets that we can use to increase the

560
00:32:20.742 --> 00:32:21.982
impact of immunotherapy.

561
00:32:23.842 --> 00:32:27.392
So our view is then that in order to really

562
00:32:28.222 --> 00:32:30.222
achieve a significant impact,

563
00:32:31.222 --> 00:32:35.142
we need to be able to translate what I refer to as the cancer immune

564
00:32:35.362 --> 00:32:38.282
dialogue. And by translation, I mean

565
00:32:39.442 --> 00:32:43.262
the word in two senses, so both literally and

566
00:32:43.342 --> 00:32:47.282
figuratively. Literally, because we really need to try and

567
00:32:47.322 --> 00:32:51.242
understand how the tumor cells and immune cells communicate with one

568
00:32:51.282 --> 00:32:51.591
another.

569
00:32:52.542 --> 00:32:54.162
And figuratively,

570
00:32:54.982 --> 00:32:55.162
we

571
00:32:56.182 --> 00:32:59.782
want to use the understanding of those mechanisms to

572
00:32:59.882 --> 00:33:03.862
translate these findings into new therapeutic

573
00:33:04.422 --> 00:33:04.882
avenues.

574
00:33:06.222 --> 00:33:09.302
So my lab asks three major questions.

575
00:33:09.842 --> 00:33:13.822
One is what's the mechanism of tumor cell intrinsic resistance?

576
00:33:13.862 --> 00:33:16.282
And once we have a better understanding, how can we break it?

577
00:33:17.382 --> 00:33:20.082
That's one major problem of immunotherapy resistance.

578
00:33:20.112 --> 00:33:22.002
Another one is T cell dysfunction.

579
00:33:22.322 --> 00:33:26.311
And also here we ask the question, what's the cause of dysfunction, and

580
00:33:26.382 --> 00:33:30.282
how can we overcome it? So I'm going to show you two little vignettes for both of

581
00:33:30.322 --> 00:33:34.202
these questions. And the third question is more recent work from

582
00:33:34.262 --> 00:33:37.862
my lab, where we really focus on the interface

583
00:33:38.522 --> 00:33:42.082
between tumor cells and T cells and address how they communicate and whether we can

584
00:33:42.142 --> 00:33:45.062
translate this into therapeutic opportunities.

585
00:33:47.042 --> 00:33:50.882
So the first question was addressed by a range of people, David Thomas and Kwee

586
00:33:50.982 --> 00:33:54.462
Kong and Martin, and what they did first is to establish a

587
00:33:54.602 --> 00:33:58.531
standardized co-culture system where they made sure that CDA T cells and

588
00:33:58.562 --> 00:34:02.442
tumor cells communicate, and that's being mediated

589
00:34:02.482 --> 00:34:06.052
by a Mart1 specific TSR that's expressed in the T cell.

590
00:34:06.622 --> 00:34:10.283
The corresponding antigen Mart1 is expressed in the tumor cell, presented by

591
00:34:10.442 --> 00:34:13.822
HLA-A2. And when we culture the two cell types,

592
00:34:14.303 --> 00:34:18.252
there's a match, there's tumor cell recognition, and if all goes well, the tumor

593
00:34:18.322 --> 00:34:22.162
cell's eliminated. If we plug in the standardized system in a cell

594
00:34:22.223 --> 00:34:25.542
line panel, we see a differential tumor sensitivity.

595
00:34:25.662 --> 00:34:29.402
So this is one example of a cell line that's completely eliminated by these Mart1

596
00:34:29.442 --> 00:34:32.803
specific T cells. But using the same standardized system,

597
00:34:33.243 --> 00:34:36.203
here's a resistant cell line that is not killed at all.

598
00:34:37.042 --> 00:34:40.342
That creates a really nice window of opportunity for doing

599
00:34:40.763 --> 00:34:44.462
genetic screens where we can screen back and forth to

600
00:34:44.562 --> 00:34:48.382
make or break resistance to T cell killing.

601
00:34:48.392 --> 00:34:52.002
Here's just one example where we do a full genome knockout

602
00:34:52.122 --> 00:34:56.082
screen in melanoma exposed to Mart1 specific T

603
00:34:56.182 --> 00:34:59.762
cells, and then we look at the guide distribution in the tumor cells that

604
00:34:59.822 --> 00:35:03.542
survive. And here we see three genes that are involved in antigen

605
00:35:03.622 --> 00:35:06.982
presentation machinery, and they're positively selected.

606
00:35:07.002 --> 00:35:10.782
That makes sense because if those genes are inactivated, these tumor cells stay

607
00:35:10.842 --> 00:35:11.792
under the T cell radar.

608
00:35:13.042 --> 00:35:16.482
From the translational point of view, it's more interesting to look at the

609
00:35:16.522 --> 00:35:20.462
depleted site, where we have several guides, like

610
00:35:20.582 --> 00:35:24.202
RNF31 and TRAF2 targeting guides,

611
00:35:25.062 --> 00:35:28.862
that are depleted. In other words, if those genes are inactivated, the

612
00:35:28.902 --> 00:35:31.672
tumor cells become much more sensitive to T cell killing.

613
00:35:32.642 --> 00:35:36.362
It occurred to us that many of those genes map to the TNF signaling

614
00:35:36.482 --> 00:35:38.962
pathway, which comes in two different arms.

615
00:35:39.002 --> 00:35:42.882
On the left-hand side, you see a survival arm, and on the right-hand side, you see

616
00:35:42.922 --> 00:35:46.722
a pro-death arm. And all the hits that we find in the screen map to the survival

617
00:35:46.782 --> 00:35:46.982
arm.

618
00:35:47.922 --> 00:35:50.802
And these two arms keep each other in check.

619
00:35:50.962 --> 00:35:53.742
So there's a balance between those signals.

620
00:35:53.842 --> 00:35:57.202
That's also seen here in a simple in vitro experiment where we use increasing

621
00:35:57.262 --> 00:35:58.222
amounts of TNF

622
00:35:59.322 --> 00:36:00.362
on these tumor cells, and you

623
00:36:01.342 --> 00:36:02.882
can see that there's very little killing.

624
00:36:03.362 --> 00:36:06.272
However, if we now inactivate one of the top hits of these screens,

625
00:36:07.022 --> 00:36:10.802
TRAF2, there's a dramatic increase in the sensitization of these tumor

626
00:36:10.882 --> 00:36:12.502
cells to T cell killing.

627
00:36:13.322 --> 00:36:17.222
We did some biochemistry here. Now with T cell exposure, if you

628
00:36:17.282 --> 00:36:17.502
have

629
00:36:18.842 --> 00:36:22.142
this T cell pressure on the tumor cells, you can see the induction of

630
00:36:22.222 --> 00:36:26.114
apoptosis if TRAF2 is inactivated.So

631
00:36:26.154 --> 00:36:30.054
if you inactivate TREF2, and we have the same data for RNF31, we

632
00:36:30.094 --> 00:36:34.054
really tip this balance from pro-survival to pro-death, and the effects are

633
00:36:34.114 --> 00:36:38.054
sufficiently robust to see this also in tumor-bearing mice, as

634
00:36:38.074 --> 00:36:41.334
in immune-proficient mouse models where the tumors are

635
00:36:41.414 --> 00:36:42.094
established.

636
00:36:43.014 --> 00:36:46.574
But if in the case of TREF2 knockout tumors, the tumors

637
00:36:46.634 --> 00:36:50.454
regress and they stay away for a very long time, and the same is seen also for

638
00:36:50.574 --> 00:36:54.034
RNF31. And the few tumors that escape here had lost the

639
00:36:54.154 --> 00:36:55.714
RNF31 guide.

640
00:36:56.754 --> 00:36:59.334
And this is completely reversible with anti-TNF.

641
00:37:00.254 --> 00:37:03.974
So these two targets, TREF2 and RNF31, if we inactivate them in

642
00:37:04.014 --> 00:37:05.974
tumor cells, we strongly

643
00:37:07.414 --> 00:37:09.554
increase their sensitivity to T cell killing.

644
00:37:10.454 --> 00:37:14.154
And therefore, they may serve as potential targets, for example, to be used in

645
00:37:14.174 --> 00:37:16.134
combination with a checkpoint blocker.

646
00:37:17.834 --> 00:37:21.534
Then one little vignette on the T cell dysfunction screens.

647
00:37:22.054 --> 00:37:25.234
This is work by Astrid, Georgie, Champu, and Pierre.

648
00:37:25.314 --> 00:37:27.654
It was about 10 man years of work.

649
00:37:28.514 --> 00:37:32.214
And you can see that this picture was taken after the paper was accepted.

650
00:37:35.014 --> 00:37:39.004
So, here we were looking at TCR stimulation,

651
00:37:39.074 --> 00:37:40.954
which comes in different forms.

652
00:37:42.214 --> 00:37:45.254
If it's really intense, it can cause fast-dependent

653
00:37:45.294 --> 00:37:48.354
activation-induced T cell death or AICD.

654
00:37:49.194 --> 00:37:52.874
If it comes in an acute form, it induces T cell cycle

655
00:37:52.934 --> 00:37:56.814
arrest. And in a chronic stimulation setting, like we

656
00:37:56.874 --> 00:38:00.664
see in tumors, it causes T cell exhaustion and dysfunction.

657
00:38:01.454 --> 00:38:05.214
And the question we ask is, is there a single genetic program that relays

658
00:38:05.224 --> 00:38:08.864
differential TCR stimulation to distinct dysfunction

659
00:38:09.074 --> 00:38:12.894
outcomes? And the way we addressed this is, again,

660
00:38:12.974 --> 00:38:14.634
using genome-wide screen

661
00:38:15.694 --> 00:38:16.194
settings,

662
00:38:17.554 --> 00:38:21.534
CRISPR knockout screens in primary mouse T cells that were exposed to

663
00:38:21.674 --> 00:38:25.594
these three modes of TCR stimulation.

664
00:38:27.234 --> 00:38:31.154
And the outcome was not that there's a single genetic

665
00:38:31.194 --> 00:38:35.174
program, but instead, it turns out that there are distinct circuitries

666
00:38:35.694 --> 00:38:39.114
that relay differential TCR stimulation to T cell

667
00:38:39.154 --> 00:38:39.714
dysfunction.

668
00:38:40.634 --> 00:38:42.254
We identified several genes,

669
00:38:43.214 --> 00:38:46.754
for example, CTBP1, which was involved only in

670
00:38:46.764 --> 00:38:50.614
dysfunction caused by chronic stimulation, but it didn't play a role in

671
00:38:50.694 --> 00:38:52.414
any of the other stress conditions.

672
00:38:53.154 --> 00:38:56.934
ICAM played a role in intense and acute TCR stimulation, but not in

673
00:38:56.954 --> 00:39:00.254
chronic stimulation. And then DEP5 played a role in all

674
00:39:00.314 --> 00:39:04.034
three dysfunction settings. If we inactivated DEP5 in

675
00:39:04.094 --> 00:39:07.324
primary T cells, we saw a boost in global translation,

676
00:39:07.894 --> 00:39:11.584
suppression of FAS expression and cell death, and a boost of T cell

677
00:39:11.654 --> 00:39:15.634
activity and proliferation. And these effects were so robust that in

678
00:39:15.674 --> 00:39:19.594
an adoptive cell transfer model, you can see that DEP5 knockout

679
00:39:19.694 --> 00:39:22.614
T cells show significant tumor control.

680
00:39:24.914 --> 00:39:28.864
All right, so moving on to the third vignette on the study on

681
00:39:28.894 --> 00:39:32.594
the interface, where Sofia and Johanna, in

682
00:39:32.634 --> 00:39:36.354
collaboration with Juan, Yolaine, Austin, and a whole range of other collaborators,

683
00:39:36.974 --> 00:39:40.154
looked at how tumor cells interact with T cells.

684
00:39:41.834 --> 00:39:45.534
They used the same standardized model that I already introduced for the

685
00:39:45.594 --> 00:39:49.414
screens. In this case, the Mart1 TCR-expressing

686
00:39:49.454 --> 00:39:53.174
T cells were labeled with a blue color, and the

687
00:39:53.214 --> 00:39:56.604
tumor cells that expressed Mart1, which were recognized by the T cells,

688
00:39:57.114 --> 00:40:00.994
were expressing a red color. And then again, we did a very simple

689
00:40:01.054 --> 00:40:01.624
co-culture,

690
00:40:02.434 --> 00:40:06.014
and looked with flow cytometry, at the

691
00:40:06.054 --> 00:40:09.834
behavior of these cells. As expected, we see the input tumor

692
00:40:09.894 --> 00:40:13.734
cell singlets here. We see the T cell singlets here, but we also

693
00:40:13.854 --> 00:40:17.634
observed a double positive population suggestive of

694
00:40:18.374 --> 00:40:22.294
doublets. Doublets, heterotypic doublets between tumor cells and T cells.

695
00:40:22.914 --> 00:40:25.514
And we could validate this under the microscope.

696
00:40:27.414 --> 00:40:30.834
So here we use a TCR antigen-matched T cell and

697
00:40:30.874 --> 00:40:34.574
melanoma cells, and they form these heterotypic clusters when they're co-cultured

698
00:40:34.594 --> 00:40:38.434
in a dish. Of course, the situation in the tumor microenvironment

699
00:40:38.514 --> 00:40:42.133
is more complex because the majority, as Tom already mentioned,

700
00:40:42.594 --> 00:40:46.474
the majority of T cells will not carry tumor-specific TCRs.

701
00:40:47.714 --> 00:40:51.514
So we try to mimic this in this simplified reductionist

702
00:40:51.794 --> 00:40:55.654
system, and we titrated in an increasing amount of non-specific T

703
00:40:55.794 --> 00:40:58.194
cells. And then we did a competition experiment and asked,

704
00:40:59.014 --> 00:41:02.844
who ends up in the doublets? Is that the non-specific T cell,

705
00:41:03.374 --> 00:41:05.554
the specific one, or is it equally distributed?

706
00:41:06.654 --> 00:41:07.754
So now if we increase

707
00:41:08.714 --> 00:41:12.654
the percentages of non-specific TCR T cells to 99%,

708
00:41:13.134 --> 00:41:16.974
we see a high enrichment of the specific matched

709
00:41:17.014 --> 00:41:20.734
TCR T cells in the doublets. In other words, these

710
00:41:20.814 --> 00:41:24.314
TCR-matched T cells out-compete non-specific T cells to form these

711
00:41:24.334 --> 00:41:26.314
heterotypic clusters with tumor cells.

712
00:41:27.294 --> 00:41:29.874
And this observation triggered our imagination.

713
00:41:30.694 --> 00:41:34.354
And we hypothesized that perhaps these heterotypic clusters can be

714
00:41:34.474 --> 00:41:38.214
used to capture tumor-reactive T cells straight from cancer

715
00:41:38.294 --> 00:41:38.854
specimens.

716
00:41:39.954 --> 00:41:43.734
Why is that relevant? Well, as already mentioned by Tom,

717
00:41:43.834 --> 00:41:47.474
tumor-reactive T cells are underrepresented in the tumor microenvironment.

718
00:41:48.064 --> 00:41:51.814
Therefore, it's been a challenge to identify and isolate those tumor-reactive T

719
00:41:51.974 --> 00:41:55.554
cells from clinical samples. And with around

720
00:41:55.734 --> 00:41:59.314
20% of complete responders in melanoma TIL

721
00:41:59.554 --> 00:42:03.034
therapy trials, there is still ample space for

722
00:42:03.094 --> 00:42:05.534
improving the benefit of TIL therapy.

723
00:42:07.334 --> 00:42:11.314
So we set out to check a series of boxes to test

724
00:42:11.324 --> 00:42:15.314
this hypothesis. The first thing, of course, was to ask

725
00:42:15.354 --> 00:42:18.644
the question: Can we identify those T cell clusters in clinical samples?

726
00:42:18.994 --> 00:42:22.094
So we built a pipeline. We collaborated with Rinan Van Hauw, John Hanna,

727
00:42:22.974 --> 00:42:26.574
and others. And we received tumor digests.

728
00:42:26.654 --> 00:42:30.514
We received a melanoma lymph node metastasis, and we made a mild

729
00:42:30.894 --> 00:42:34.778
tumor digest.We ran some flow cytometry

730
00:42:34.818 --> 00:42:37.478
analysis and looked for singlets and clusters.

731
00:42:38.027 --> 00:42:39.898
And this is a typical plot that we got.

732
00:42:40.458 --> 00:42:44.298
Here we see tumor cell singlets, large population, T

733
00:42:44.378 --> 00:42:48.198
cell singlets, and indeed, we see this double positive population on the top

734
00:42:48.258 --> 00:42:52.098
right corner suggestive of T cell tumor clusters.

735
00:42:52.858 --> 00:42:56.818
Since we got these samples from lymph node metastasis, we also looked for T cell

736
00:42:56.858 --> 00:43:00.808
APC doublets. And again, we see the presence of these

737
00:43:00.878 --> 00:43:03.328
double positive cells. Small percentages,

738
00:43:04.238 --> 00:43:07.778
but to give you some numbers, the CD8 T cell clusters comprise

739
00:43:08.698 --> 00:43:10.538
about 1.4% of all

740
00:43:12.438 --> 00:43:14.828
cells in these tumor samples,

741
00:43:15.638 --> 00:43:17.798
and of the total CD8 T cells,

742
00:43:18.738 --> 00:43:21.138
we see that about 12% is in clusters.

743
00:43:21.648 --> 00:43:24.778
And we see this in all out of 21 patients that we've analyzed.

744
00:43:26.318 --> 00:43:30.008
So we see these heterotypic clusters between CD8 T cells and

745
00:43:30.078 --> 00:43:32.498
tumor cells, and CD8 T cells and APCs.

746
00:43:32.698 --> 00:43:35.978
We can identify them and isolate them from clinical samples,

747
00:43:36.598 --> 00:43:37.898
but we're still not completely

748
00:43:38.938 --> 00:43:41.278
sure whether we're not looking at an artifact.

749
00:43:41.338 --> 00:43:43.148
So we wanted to have some visual confirmation.

750
00:43:44.058 --> 00:43:47.958
We did two approaches. One is multiplex immunohistochemistry,

751
00:43:47.978 --> 00:43:51.838
and here you see some niches where the T

752
00:43:51.938 --> 00:43:55.878
cells in blue, tumor cells in red, and APCs in yellow are really

753
00:43:55.898 --> 00:43:59.418
residing in each other's vicinity, but that's still

754
00:43:59.498 --> 00:44:00.838
not definitive evidence.

755
00:44:01.718 --> 00:44:05.458
So then we made use of image stream flow imaging, which is like a

756
00:44:05.578 --> 00:44:09.538
flow cytometer, but for every cell that passes the laser, it makes a nice picture.

757
00:44:10.238 --> 00:44:13.158
So here in the bright field, we look at a large cell and a small cell.

758
00:44:13.218 --> 00:44:13.898
The large cell

759
00:44:15.018 --> 00:44:18.518
lights up with a tumor marker, the small cell with a CD8

760
00:44:18.838 --> 00:44:21.958
marker. And in the merge, you can see that they're nicely conjugated.

761
00:44:23.278 --> 00:44:26.798
One row lower is one of our favorite images.

762
00:44:26.918 --> 00:44:30.818
It's one APC binding simultaneously to two CD8 T cells.

763
00:44:31.098 --> 00:44:35.038
And here you see these structures that are highly reminiscent of an

764
00:44:35.078 --> 00:44:38.148
immunological synapse, which suggests that this is in functional

765
00:44:38.178 --> 00:44:42.118
interaction. We also see larger clusters, one tumor cell,

766
00:44:42.178 --> 00:44:45.918
two CD8 T cells, and one APC, and that's why we refer to this as

767
00:44:46.058 --> 00:44:47.618
clusters and no longer as doublets.

768
00:44:49.218 --> 00:44:52.938
So then we asked, can we discover new biology of these

769
00:44:53.018 --> 00:44:55.898
clusters, and are there any therapeutic opportunities?

770
00:44:56.898 --> 00:45:00.878
So we built this pipeline where we now separate the singlets

771
00:45:00.938 --> 00:45:04.398
from the clusters a-and perform a single-cell RNA-TCR

772
00:45:04.418 --> 00:45:05.018
sequencing.

773
00:45:07.638 --> 00:45:11.338
In the UMAPs, we see these three cell types, tumor cells, T cells,

774
00:45:11.438 --> 00:45:15.278
APCs. The T cells come in 14 different cell

775
00:45:15.378 --> 00:45:19.158
states, exactly as you would expect it, and in agreement with literature.

776
00:45:19.538 --> 00:45:23.298
But now we can ask an interesting question, and that is, are the

777
00:45:23.358 --> 00:45:27.218
reactive cell states equally distributed over T cell singlets and clusters?

778
00:45:28.898 --> 00:45:32.228
And the answer is, they're not equally distributed because there is a strong

779
00:45:32.278 --> 00:45:36.248
enrichment specifically of exhausted and proliferative cell states in

780
00:45:36.258 --> 00:45:39.118
the clusters in comparison with T cell singlets.

781
00:45:41.078 --> 00:45:43.318
We also looked at T cell reactivity gene signatures.

782
00:45:43.358 --> 00:45:46.478
If you look at the top right, all these light blue bars

783
00:45:47.138 --> 00:45:51.098
represent individual single T cells, and you can see that they're highly

784
00:45:51.158 --> 00:45:54.988
reactive for a viral antigen specificity signature,

785
00:45:55.558 --> 00:45:59.538
suggesting that these singlets are bystander T cells in the

786
00:45:59.618 --> 00:46:00.588
tumor microenvironment.

787
00:46:01.418 --> 00:46:04.938
In contrast, if you move to the left with the green and the purple bars for T

788
00:46:05.058 --> 00:46:08.308
cells from APC and tumor clusters, we can see that those

789
00:46:08.338 --> 00:46:11.978
clusters are highly enriched for tumor antigen specificity.

790
00:46:13.278 --> 00:46:17.138
We also looked by single-cell sequencing for the TCR repertoire,

791
00:46:17.558 --> 00:46:21.298
and we see that there's an increase in clonal TCRs specifically in the

792
00:46:21.358 --> 00:46:24.938
clusters, and that suggests that those T cells have undergone selective

793
00:46:24.958 --> 00:46:28.278
expansion and are active against the tumors in the tumor microenvironment.

794
00:46:29.478 --> 00:46:33.438
But then, of course, the $64,000 question, are these T

795
00:46:33.558 --> 00:46:35.318
cells from clusters better killers?

796
00:46:36.678 --> 00:46:40.558
So we now expanded the pipeline once again and now include

797
00:46:40.678 --> 00:46:43.978
one step, which we call rep for rapid expansion, which is very

798
00:46:44.038 --> 00:46:47.618
similar to what John Hanna and others use for TIL therapy of

799
00:46:47.638 --> 00:46:51.538
patients. So after the physical separations of singlets

800
00:46:51.578 --> 00:46:53.857
from clusters, we individually

801
00:46:55.258 --> 00:46:59.178
expand those T cell populations, and then they're ready for some

802
00:47:00.058 --> 00:47:00.538
business

803
00:47:01.358 --> 00:47:04.678
essays to look at their tumor killing capacity.

804
00:47:04.718 --> 00:47:08.418
Here, if you look at the cytokine production, we already get a little hint

805
00:47:08.898 --> 00:47:10.598
because the T cells

