00:57:23.846 --> 00:57:27.706
T-cells and T-cells in clusters. It's too early to give you the details,

988
00:57:28.506 --> 00:57:29.966
but it looks quite interesting.

989
00:57:30.486 --> 00:57:30.786
Thank you.

990
00:57:31.246 --> 00:57:32.446
One more question on this side.

991
00:57:32.686 --> 00:57:32.966
Okay.

992
00:57:33.806 --> 00:57:37.706
Great job. Really, really nice. You show in the beginning that some tumor

993
00:57:37.726 --> 00:57:40.786
cells are resistant to cell death by engaging with T-cells.

994
00:57:41.346 --> 00:57:44.726
So from the cluster work, when you find them together in the

995
00:57:44.886 --> 00:57:48.706
patient, does the tumor cells ever resistant to that

996
00:57:48.746 --> 00:57:49.386
contact too?

997
00:57:49.786 --> 00:57:53.626
It's a very good question, and I just mentioned how we characterize the tumor cells

998
00:57:53.666 --> 00:57:56.646
that specifically bind to these T-cells.

999
00:57:56.686 --> 00:58:00.406
Of course, it's important to be aware that we're making a

1000
00:58:00.546 --> 00:58:03.906
snapshot, right? So we're looking at one

1001
00:58:04.046 --> 00:58:06.966
situation in time, one moment. At that moment,

1002
00:58:08.306 --> 00:58:10.766
most of the T-cells are singlet and some are in clusters.

1003
00:58:11.326 --> 00:58:15.106
If you would have taken the sample one day earlier or maybe 15 minutes

1004
00:58:15.146 --> 00:58:18.106
later, the distribution may have been a little bit different.

1005
00:58:18.486 --> 00:58:22.266
So we're not saying that all T-cell singlets

1006
00:58:23.046 --> 00:58:25.306
are the wrong T-cells, or

1007
00:58:26.566 --> 00:58:29.826
that they are not recognizing tumors at all.

1008
00:58:30.906 --> 00:58:34.446
What we do see and claim is that the

1009
00:58:34.486 --> 00:58:38.466
T-cells that are in clusters are very strongly enriched for tumor

1010
00:58:38.476 --> 00:58:42.306
reactivity. But it's a snapshot, and it's very

1011
00:58:42.366 --> 00:58:46.006
well possible that a low frequency of the single

1012
00:58:46.106 --> 00:58:49.986
T-cells also carries the right TCRs, and that's exactly what

1013
00:58:50.006 --> 00:58:51.006
we're looking at right now.

1014
00:58:51.726 --> 00:58:52.726
Great. Thank you.

1015
00:58:52.746 --> 00:58:52.946
Thank you.

1016
00:58:53.926 --> 00:58:54.666
Thanks again, Daniel.

1017
00:58:58.106 --> 00:59:01.946
So the third presentation this morning is from Larry

1018
00:59:02.046 --> 00:59:05.806
Fong, who's going to, I believe, talk to us about myeloid

1019
00:59:05.846 --> 00:59:06.905
cells in prostate cancer.

1020
00:59:08.866 --> 00:59:12.766
All right. Terrific. Well, I wanted to thank the organizers for

1021
00:59:12.786 --> 00:59:14.186
the opportunity to present.

1022
00:59:15.066 --> 00:59:18.866
And I am going to talk about myeloid-mediated immune suppression with an

1023
00:59:18.906 --> 00:59:20.526
emphasis on prostate cancer. But,

1024
00:59:21.386 --> 00:59:24.506
I think we're actually finding these cell types in other types of cancers.

1025
00:59:24.566 --> 00:59:28.426
And so I'll touch upon that briefly at the end. These are my disclosures.

1026
00:59:28.446 --> 00:59:32.326
And so, as we think about this session, hot versus cold, you could

1027
00:59:32.806 --> 00:59:36.486
think about it, also as well with regards to checkpoint inhibition,

1028
00:59:36.586 --> 00:59:38.426
into binning cancers into the sensitive

1029
00:59:39.826 --> 00:59:43.326
tumors to anti-PD-1 versus those that are refractory.

1030
00:59:43.336 --> 00:59:47.226
And so I'm going to focus on the refractory side and, in this

1031
00:59:47.286 --> 00:59:51.066
case, focus in prostate cancer. And just to

1032
00:59:51.106 --> 00:59:54.896
drive this point home about the refractoriness of prostate cancers, we now

1033
00:59:54.966 --> 00:59:58.566
have eight phase III clinical trials with different checkpoint

1034
00:59:58.586 --> 01:00:02.026
inhibitors that failed to show any survival advantage.

1035
01:00:02.066 --> 01:00:04.966
And so this is one of the clinical trials that looks at

1036
01:00:05.046 --> 01:00:06.266
atezolizumab.

1037
01:00:07.266 --> 01:00:09.746
Those patients receiving that drug are in the blue

1038
01:00:11.226 --> 01:00:15.066
curve, and you could argue that there's no difference, but you could also argue

1039
01:00:15.126 --> 01:00:19.086
that perhaps these patients receiving atezolizumab actually are doing a little bit

1040
01:00:19.226 --> 01:00:19.526
worse.

1041
01:00:20.376 --> 01:00:24.186
And so, when we think about immunotherapy and prostate cancer,

1042
01:00:25.506 --> 01:00:29.146
just to remind folks, there's actually an FDA-approved

1043
01:00:29.186 --> 01:00:33.166
immunotherapy for prostate cancer, and this is something I had worked on when

1044
01:00:33.226 --> 01:00:36.936
I was a postdoc a long time ago. But

1045
01:00:36.946 --> 01:00:40.846
this is basically an autologous cellular immunotherapy

1046
01:00:40.856 --> 01:00:44.756
that is loaded with prostatic acid phosphatase as

1047
01:00:44.786 --> 01:00:48.046
the antigen. And this was at a time when dendritic cell

1048
01:00:48.086 --> 01:00:51.006
vaccines were very much at the fore.

1049
01:00:51.016 --> 01:00:54.526
And in a couple of randomized clinical trials, it actually

1050
01:00:54.586 --> 01:00:58.226
showed about a four-month overall survival advantage.

1051
01:00:58.266 --> 01:01:00.026
And so for that, this was FDA approved.

1052
01:01:00.536 --> 01:01:02.186
But there was a lot of

1053
01:01:03.926 --> 01:01:07.366
challenges in terms of adopting this therapy because the patients who receive these

1054
01:01:07.426 --> 01:01:11.090
treatments don't have objective clinical responses.Their

1055
01:01:11.110 --> 01:01:13.630
tumors don't shrink, their PSAs don't go down.

1056
01:01:13.750 --> 01:01:17.610
And so this has always been, even though this is still a therapy we

1057
01:01:17.670 --> 01:01:20.900
can prescribe, it's not really used very much.

1058
01:01:21.850 --> 01:01:25.550
Now, when we actually studied this treatment, we showed that it actually

1059
01:01:25.590 --> 01:01:29.580
functions as a vaccine, so it induces these immune clonotypes that

1060
01:01:29.590 --> 01:01:32.510
are below the threshold of detection at baseline.

1061
01:01:32.550 --> 01:01:34.470
They circulate in the blood at high frequency.

1062
01:01:34.510 --> 01:01:37.730
The T cells, about a third of them T cell clones end up in the

1063
01:01:37.770 --> 01:01:41.550
tissues. But one of the things that we found was if you look at these patients

1064
01:01:42.030 --> 01:01:45.610
treated with sipuleucel-T, in this case, this is prior to

1065
01:01:45.730 --> 01:01:47.910
surgery, so this is a neoadjuvant trial.

1066
01:01:48.390 --> 01:01:51.810
We can actually see recruitment of the T cells into the tumor

1067
01:01:51.910 --> 01:01:55.770
microenvironment in those patients who are

1068
01:01:55.830 --> 01:01:58.250
treated. But down on the bottom here,

1069
01:01:59.090 --> 01:02:02.990
when you look in the tissues, these T cells are actually hung up in what we

1070
01:02:03.050 --> 01:02:07.030
called at the time the interface, so the invasive

1071
01:02:07.130 --> 01:02:10.570
margin that borders tumors from normal tissues.

1072
01:02:10.610 --> 01:02:14.130
And so this is what we now call an excluded phenotype.

1073
01:02:14.210 --> 01:02:18.170
So this vaccine was inducing T cells, but for whatever reason, they're

1074
01:02:18.210 --> 01:02:20.770
not able to actually migrate into the tumor centers.

1075
01:02:20.810 --> 01:02:24.670
And so we really wanted to understand the mechanisms of resistance

1076
01:02:25.050 --> 01:02:26.730
in the context of prostate cancer.

1077
01:02:27.230 --> 01:02:30.910
And so, one of the approaches that we took was actually

1078
01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:31.310
studying

1079
01:02:32.510 --> 01:02:34.250
biopsy tissues from patients

1080
01:02:35.270 --> 01:02:37.290
with different states of prostate cancer.

1081
01:02:37.350 --> 01:02:40.250
So localized disease, metastatic

1082
01:02:40.310 --> 01:02:44.170
hormone-sensitive disease. And then when you treat prostate cancer

1083
01:02:44.210 --> 01:02:47.270
with hormonal therapy, essentially ablating androgens,

1084
01:02:47.950 --> 01:02:51.570
patients typically progress to castration-resistant disease.

1085
01:02:51.630 --> 01:02:53.840
And this is the lethal form of prostate cancer.

1086
01:02:54.230 --> 01:02:57.910
And we subjected this to multi-omics single cell, and you can

1087
01:02:57.950 --> 01:03:00.660
identify the different cell types within these biopsies.

1088
01:03:01.470 --> 01:03:05.440
And we focused on the myeloid compartment, and I want to highlight, this

1089
01:03:05.490 --> 01:03:08.970
work was led by Aram and Zheng Hua.

1090
01:03:11.350 --> 01:03:14.910
And Aram actually just presented at this meeting with a

1091
01:03:14.970 --> 01:03:15.980
subsequent story that I'll

1092
01:03:16.910 --> 01:03:20.670
highlight. Now, when we think about the myeloid

1093
01:03:20.710 --> 01:03:24.610
compartment, Tom discussed these classifiers

1094
01:03:24.650 --> 01:03:28.090
of M1 and M2. When you actually look at the myeloid

1095
01:03:28.110 --> 01:03:31.910
compartment with single-cell methodologies, you can

1096
01:03:31.970 --> 01:03:35.210
see that there's actually considerably higher level of

1097
01:03:35.270 --> 01:03:39.080
heterogeneity, where we can actually identify discrete populations that

1098
01:03:39.110 --> 01:03:43.030
can be identified based upon specific genes that stand

1099
01:03:43.110 --> 01:03:45.830
out. And one that stood out to us was actually these

1100
01:03:45.970 --> 01:03:49.670
SPP1-high tumor-associated macrophages, or

1101
01:03:49.730 --> 01:03:53.330
TAMs. And you can see as prostate cancer progresses

1102
01:03:53.410 --> 01:03:57.210
along the continuum within the TME, the abundance of these myeloid

1103
01:03:57.270 --> 01:04:01.210
cells actually go up. And so this is actually the quantitation of that, where you

1104
01:04:01.250 --> 01:04:02.890
can see this increase in frequency.

1105
01:04:03.230 --> 01:04:07.070
But the other thing that I wanted to highlight was that these can represent

1106
01:04:07.150 --> 01:04:11.030
about 20% of the myeloid compartment within prostate cancer.

1107
01:04:11.470 --> 01:04:15.130
And then the other component is you can see there's actually a fairly broad

1108
01:04:15.140 --> 01:04:18.010
distribution in prostate cancer.

1109
01:04:19.570 --> 01:04:23.390
Now, oftentimes, when we think about myeloid cells,

1110
01:04:24.190 --> 01:04:28.090
we can think about their immunosuppressive capacity, and so we

1111
01:04:28.130 --> 01:04:30.069
can apply gene signatures for that.

1112
01:04:30.080 --> 01:04:33.230
And you can see that a few of these different populations have

1113
01:04:33.290 --> 01:04:34.900
immunosuppressive gene signatures.

1114
01:04:35.410 --> 01:04:39.210
Another way of identifying myeloid cells has

1115
01:04:39.230 --> 01:04:43.220
been TREM2. And so if you look at that, you can see that actually quite a

1116
01:04:43.270 --> 01:04:46.230
few different myeloid populations actually

1117
01:04:47.050 --> 01:04:50.960
overexpress TREM2. SPP1 myeloid cells have TREM2, but they're

1118
01:04:50.970 --> 01:04:52.930
not the highest expressers of that.

1119
01:04:53.319 --> 01:04:56.850
And so I think a lot of thinking about the myeloid compartment is whether you're a

1120
01:04:56.910 --> 01:05:00.750
lumper or a splitter in terms of how you want to classify.

1121
01:05:01.470 --> 01:05:04.910
If we actually look at this immunosuppression

1122
01:05:05.130 --> 01:05:08.610
signature, you can see not only are the SPP1 high

1123
01:05:08.670 --> 01:05:12.479
TAMs elevated in the suppression signature, there are actually other

1124
01:05:12.479 --> 01:05:15.800
populations that could also be contributing to

1125
01:05:15.810 --> 01:05:19.700
immunosuppression. But we wanted to drill down on these SPP1 TAMs and

1126
01:05:19.750 --> 01:05:22.590
actually test functionally whether they're suppressive.

1127
01:05:23.030 --> 01:05:26.570
Now, SPP1 is the gene that encodes for

1128
01:05:26.650 --> 01:05:30.410
osteopontin, and this protein is actually expressed

1129
01:05:30.470 --> 01:05:33.770
across multiple cell types, including multiple myeloid

1130
01:05:33.850 --> 01:05:37.410
populations as well as other stromal components.

1131
01:05:37.470 --> 01:05:40.910
And it's already known to play critical roles in bone remodeling as well as

1132
01:05:41.330 --> 01:05:44.870
wound healing and metastasis. We're not going to talk about SPP1

1133
01:05:44.930 --> 01:05:47.080
functionally in this presentation.

1134
01:05:47.090 --> 01:05:50.460
We're just using it as a marker for myeloid population.

1135
01:05:50.930 --> 01:05:54.760
And so what we wanted to do to test these functionally was actually to bring this

1136
01:05:54.850 --> 01:05:58.250
back into a mouse model. And so we utilized a mouse that

1137
01:05:59.610 --> 01:06:00.670
expresses GFP

1138
01:06:01.730 --> 01:06:04.150
with SPP1. We can actually

1139
01:06:05.230 --> 01:06:08.670
treat these mice with this mouse tumor with hormonal

1140
01:06:08.690 --> 01:06:12.210
therapy. You can see the tumors initially respond, and then they go on to

1141
01:06:12.270 --> 01:06:15.350
progress, not unlike castration-resistant disease.

1142
01:06:15.360 --> 01:06:19.110
And what we found is that the myeloid compartment actually, to a certain extent,

1143
01:06:19.230 --> 01:06:22.650
recapitulated the myeloid compartment within our patients.

1144
01:06:22.730 --> 01:06:24.990
And so we went ahead to study these.

1145
01:06:25.530 --> 01:06:29.350
And with these SPP1 GFP mice, what that allowed us to do was

1146
01:06:29.710 --> 01:06:33.450
basically be able to sort out these myeloid cells to

1147
01:06:33.490 --> 01:06:36.620
test them functionally. And what we found was that these

1148
01:06:37.330 --> 01:06:41.310
myeloid cells do indeed suppress in vitro, whether you look

1149
01:06:41.430 --> 01:06:44.690
in a proliferation assay or a cytokine production assay.

1150
01:06:45.290 --> 01:06:48.490
And then if you actually looked with regards to in vivo

1151
01:06:48.930 --> 01:06:52.710
immunosuppression, if you actually, in this mouse model, treat the

1152
01:06:52.750 --> 01:06:56.700
mice with combination checkpoint inhibition, you can see with the red curve that

1153
01:06:56.730 --> 01:06:59.610
there's actually some clinical activity.

1154
01:06:59.630 --> 01:07:03.450
But if you adoptively transfer in more of these SPP1 high TAMs, you

1155
01:07:03.470 --> 01:07:07.390
basically negate that efficacy. And this is just

1156
01:07:07.450 --> 01:07:11.390
looking with regards to exhaustion, where you can actually

1157
01:07:11.450 --> 01:07:14.910
see with checkpoint inhibition you reduce T cell exhaustion, but when you give more

1158
01:07:14.970 --> 01:07:18.630
of these SPP1 high TAMs, you actually, again,

1159
01:07:18.830 --> 01:07:22.810
negate that phenotype. Now, as we think about ways that these myeloid

1160
01:07:22.850 --> 01:07:26.230
cells can suppress, we looked at the different

1161
01:07:26.510 --> 01:07:30.100
molecular pathways that are operative in these TAMs, and one of them that stood out

1162
01:07:30.130 --> 01:07:33.426
to us is the hypoxia pathwayAnd we know in the context of

1163
01:07:33.446 --> 01:07:37.226
hypoxia, you get induction of many different mechanisms,

1164
01:07:37.326 --> 01:07:40.786
but one of them is actually the induction of these

1165
01:07:40.826 --> 01:07:44.346
ectoenzymes, CD39 and CD73, that

1166
01:07:44.726 --> 01:07:48.086
catabolize extracellular ATP, which is

1167
01:07:48.706 --> 01:07:52.066
released in cell death. That's actually immunostimulatory

1168
01:07:52.726 --> 01:07:56.186
to extracellular free adenosine, which we know is

1169
01:07:56.206 --> 01:07:59.856
potently immunosuppressive. And we can see that these SPP1 high

1170
01:07:59.946 --> 01:08:02.926
TAMs actually express high levels of CD73.

1171
01:08:03.416 --> 01:08:07.046
And in fact, we can actually detect these SPP1 high TAMs

1172
01:08:07.086 --> 01:08:10.116
producing adenosine into the culture supernatants.

1173
01:08:10.966 --> 01:08:14.706
So then, the question was, now that we identified this pathway, can we actually

1174
01:08:14.726 --> 01:08:17.547
block it therapeutically? And the answer to that is yes.

1175
01:08:17.606 --> 01:08:21.387
In this case, we looked at an adenosine A2A receptor

1176
01:08:21.427 --> 01:08:22.927
antagonist, zafirlukast.

1177
01:08:23.786 --> 01:08:27.366
And you can see in this case, a checkpoint inhibition just with

1178
01:08:27.427 --> 01:08:30.906
anti-PD-1 alone, really not doing very much.

1179
01:08:31.066 --> 01:08:34.856
But if you use this A2A receptor antagonist, you can actually see some

1180
01:08:34.866 --> 01:08:38.816
clinical efficacy, but the two together actually work better.

1181
01:08:38.816 --> 01:08:42.786
And you actually induce many more of these polyfunctional T cells in this

1182
01:08:42.826 --> 01:08:46.806
context. So then the final component of this initial

1183
01:08:46.866 --> 01:08:50.396
half of the talk is, does this actually have any consequence in

1184
01:08:50.427 --> 01:08:54.286
patients? And so I introduced to you at the beginning atezolizumab in that

1185
01:08:54.306 --> 01:08:57.326
phase three trial showing no efficacy.

1186
01:08:57.387 --> 01:08:59.166
In this case, we tested it either

1187
01:08:59.967 --> 01:09:03.587
with zafirlukast in combination or zafirlukast as a

1188
01:09:03.646 --> 01:09:07.056
monotherapy. And what we found is we can now see clinical

1189
01:09:07.106 --> 01:09:09.146
responses in about

1190
01:09:10.026 --> 01:09:13.726
20% of our patients with castration-resistant disease.

1191
01:09:14.406 --> 01:09:17.946
And this is just an example of one of the clinical responses that we

1192
01:09:18.246 --> 01:09:22.026
saw. But when we actually looked at the pretreatment

1193
01:09:22.106 --> 01:09:25.576
biopsies from these patients, one of the things we found was that these

1194
01:09:25.666 --> 01:09:29.346
responders at baseline had really high levels of these

1195
01:09:29.507 --> 01:09:33.246
SPP1 TAMs, whereas the non-responders did

1196
01:09:33.257 --> 01:09:36.967
not. And so what we would argue is that for

1197
01:09:37.007 --> 01:09:40.746
those subset of patients that have a lot of these SPP1 high

1198
01:09:40.806 --> 01:09:44.746
TAMs, perhaps blocking the adenosine pathway

1199
01:09:45.186 --> 01:09:49.036
could be a therapeutic approach. But then how do we think about these

1200
01:09:49.106 --> 01:09:52.587
other patients that don't have these SPP1 TAMs?

1201
01:09:53.606 --> 01:09:53.786
So,

1202
01:09:55.006 --> 01:09:58.306
are there other mechanisms that we could think about that elicit this

1203
01:09:58.346 --> 01:09:59.766
immunotherapeutic resistance?

1204
01:10:00.616 --> 01:10:04.186
And so, what we've since done, and again, this is

1205
01:10:04.546 --> 01:10:07.916
data that Aram just presented yesterday,

1206
01:10:08.466 --> 01:10:12.226
was expand our assessment of biopsies

1207
01:10:12.366 --> 01:10:16.066
in the castration-resistant disease setting to include

1208
01:10:16.086 --> 01:10:19.786
multiple sites of metastasis so that we could dive into this

1209
01:10:19.846 --> 01:10:22.986
further. And you can see with regards to the myeloid cell

1210
01:10:23.086 --> 01:10:26.886
populations, if you look at the soft tissues such as

1211
01:10:26.926 --> 01:10:30.346
prostate or even in liver biopsies, you can see the myeloid

1212
01:10:30.366 --> 01:10:33.426
compositions that we talked about a little earlier.

1213
01:10:33.446 --> 01:10:37.246
But if you look in bone, you actually don't see very many of these

1214
01:10:37.306 --> 01:10:39.006
myeloid cells that we've been focusing on.

1215
01:10:39.066 --> 01:10:42.946
Instead, you see a predominance of neutrophils.

1216
01:10:43.706 --> 01:10:46.786
And so if we look here in terms of the quantitation of this, I'm

1217
01:10:47.806 --> 01:10:51.326
sorry some of this got blocked out, but essentially what this shows is a

1218
01:10:51.386 --> 01:10:55.266
quantitation where there are really high levels of neutrophils

1219
01:10:55.306 --> 01:10:56.106
within the bone,

1220
01:10:57.106 --> 01:11:00.886
and really a low representation of these myeloid cells that we've been focused

1221
01:11:00.946 --> 01:11:04.516
on. And again, Aram has presented that at this

1222
01:11:04.566 --> 01:11:08.555
meeting. And so when we look at these neutrophils and

1223
01:11:08.566 --> 01:11:12.346
drill down on them, we can actually use naming conventions that are

1224
01:11:12.446 --> 01:11:16.176
